  <!-- FAMILY -->
  <section id="family" class="trib-section">
    <div class="tw">
      <div class="trib-section-head">
        <div class="trib-eyebrow">Family · Legacy · Love</div>
        <h2 class="trib-h2">Beloved Husband.<br/>Devoted Father.</h2>
        <p class="trib-lede">His love at home powered his service in the movement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="trib-two">
        <div class="trib-fig" style="aspect-ratio:1/1;">
          <img src="/assets/img/libations/andrew-group-2.jpg"
               alt="Andrew Joseph Jr. with family and movement — the love that powered the work."/>
        </div>
        <div class="trib-prose">
          <p>Andrew Joseph&nbsp;Jr. was a husband to Deanna — the woman who, by every account, walked every step of this fight beside him. He was a father to Andrew Joseph&nbsp;III, to Deja. He was a son of New Orleans, a son of Grambling, an uncle, a cousin, a friend, a mentor, a comrade.</p>
          <p>He carried more grief than any one human being should ever have to carry, and he turned that grief into a shield for other people&rsquo;s children. He turned a name into a movement. He turned a tragedy into a turning point — the very phrase his foundation uses to describe its own beginning.</p>
          <p>He is preceded in death by his son and namesake, Andrew Joseph&nbsp;III, who he can now finally see again.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="trib-survivors">
        <div class="trib-survivor">
          <div class="role">Wife</div>
          <div class="name">Deanna Joseph</div>
        </div>
        <div class="trib-survivor">
          <div class="role">Daughter</div>
          <div class="name">Deja Joseph</div>
        </div>
        <div class="trib-survivor">
          <div class="role">Son · Preceded him in death</div>
          <div class="name">Andrew Joseph III</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TIMELINE -->
  <section id="timeline" class="trib-section">
    <div class="tw">
      <div class="trib-section-head">
        <div class="trib-eyebrow">A Life of Service</div>
        <h2 class="trib-h2">Defining<br/>Moments.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="trib-timeline">
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">New Orleans</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Born &amp; raised in southern Louisiana.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Shaped by the family, faith, and cultural traditions of his hometown.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">Grambling State</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Bachelor&rsquo;s &amp; Master&rsquo;s in Criminal Justice.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Begins career interning with legal groups supporting youth and families in rural Louisiana.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">Late 1990s &ndash; mid-2000s</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Lead Assistant Principal, alternative learning environments.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Works with adjudicated youth across the southern Louisiana region. Earns recognition among educators and juvenile justice departments.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">2005</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Hurricane Katrina forces the family to Tampa.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">The Josephs settle in the Tampa Bay area. Andrew&nbsp;III begins playing youth football at Riverview Raiders Field in Brandon.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row major"><div class="trib-tl-when">Feb 7, 2014</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Andrew Joseph&nbsp;III, 14, is killed near the Florida State Fair.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">AJ&nbsp;III and ~100 other minors are ejected by Hillsborough County Sheriff&rsquo;s deputies. He is detained, transported away from the main gate, and directed across Interstate&nbsp;4 to reach his ride. He is struck and killed. His parents are never called.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">2014 &ndash; 2015</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">The Andrew Joseph Foundation &mdash; &ldquo;AJ Soars&rdquo; &mdash; is born.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">A 501(c)(3) dedicated to children&rsquo;s rights, child safety, conflict resolution education, and family support. Out of grief, Andrew and Deanna build something.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">2015</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Black Lives Matter Grassroots stands with the Joseph family.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Under the leadership of co-founder Dr.&nbsp;Melina Abdullah. The family begins standing with the movement right back.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">2016</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Federal wrongful death lawsuit filed.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Against the Hillsborough County Sheriff&rsquo;s Office, the Florida State Fair Authority, and the Hillsborough County School District.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">2016 &ndash; 2023</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Florida State Fair safety reforms.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Minors under 17 must be accompanied by an adult 21+ after 6&nbsp;p.m. Ejected minors held in supervised waiting area. Parents notified when minors are ejected. Additional cameras, deputies, and lighting.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">July 12, 2020</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Riverwalk paver unveiled.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">The Andrew Joseph Foundation and the Restorative Justice Coalition unveil a granite paver on the Tampa Riverwalk honoring AJ&nbsp;III&rsquo;s life.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">c. 2020 &ndash; 2026</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Rapid Response Coordinator, Black Lives Matter Grassroots.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Travels nationally to be on-the-ground with families harmed by police violence. Speaks at Netroots Nation. Partners with the Love Not Blood Campaign.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row major"><div class="trib-tl-when">Sept 22, 2022</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Federal jury verdict — $15 million.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">A 10-person federal jury finds HCSO 90% responsible for AJ&nbsp;III&rsquo;s death and awards the family $15&nbsp;million. Five days later, BLM Grassroots and 12 Justice families issue a national call to pass the Ending Qualified Immunity Act.</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row"><div class="trib-tl-when">Feb 2024</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Ten years since AJ&nbsp;III&rsquo;s death.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Family holds a candlelight vigil at the Partico Café in downtown Tampa. Andrew recommits: &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve been boots on the ground since day one.&rdquo;</p></div></div>
        <div class="trib-tl-row major"><div class="trib-tl-when">May 16, 2026</div><div><h3 class="trib-tl-h">Andrew Joseph&nbsp;Jr. transitions.</h3><p class="trib-tl-p">Survived by his wife Deanna, his daughter Deja, and an extended movement family of comrades, Justice families, and chapter leaders across the country. Preceded in death by his son and namesake, Andrew Joseph&nbsp;III, whom he can now finally see again.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

